Probably the most exciting sighting for me.  We came on a pack of two wild dogs with this very fresh impala kill. When they ate their fill we notice this leopardess sitting right on the other side of our vehicle.  When the dogs left she drug the kill to a tree but before she could take it up a new pack of dogs with pups stole the impala and chased her up a very small tree.  She was barely out of their reach.  Exciting times.

The African wild dog, AKA as Cape hunting dog, painted dog or just plain “the dogs.” Frequently the true African safari aficionados will select reserves that will increase their chances of seeing these very successful predators hunt.  They work as a pack to exhaust their prey.

The rangers and trackers do a great job of finding the wildlife.  Alarm calls of the monkeys and birds alert them to a possible predator in the area.  Or tracks in the road can tell them what animal, how long since they walked by and frequently if it’s male or female.  And to get these images they have to drive around him through the thick bush to get in front.  Then as he passes us in the road we do it all over again and again.  Witnessing the rangers and trackers working together is very impressive.

Cheetah in the morning in the Mara.  The fastest land animal is such a nervous Nellie.  They’re low man on the predator totem pole and very often lose their kill to a lion, leopard, hyena or even vultures can chase them off their meal.  They have to eat as fast and as much as they can before being spotted.
